· CASH-OUT OPTION
Shippers who choose not to subscribe to Banking and Balancing Service under Part 3, Rate Schedule BBS, will be cashed-out on a daily basis by the Company as follows: On days when gas transported to or for a Shipper exceeds the quantities of gas delivered into the Company’s system on the Shipper’s behalf, Shipper will purchase such excess quantities from Company at the higher of 1) 120% of the daily Index Price for the day on which such Excess Quantities were delivered to or for Shipper as reported in the PLATTS Gas Daily publication, in the Daily price survey section under the heading “Transco, zone 6 non-N.Y.” Midpoint, or 2) 120% of the Daily Index price for the day on which such Excess Quantities were delivered to or for Shipper as reported in the PLATTS Gas Daily publication, in the Daily price survey section under the heading “Transco, zone 5 del.” Midpoint. On days when gas delivered into the Company’s system on a Shipper’s behalf exceeds the quantities transported to or for the Shipper, Company will purchase those excess delivered quantities from the Shipper at the lower of 1) 80% of the Daily Index price for the day on which such excess delivered quantities were received by Company as reported in the PLATTS Gas Daily publication, in the Daily price survey section under the heading “Transco, zone 6 non-N.Y.” Midpoint, or 2) 80% of the Daily Index price for the day on which such excess delivered quantities were received by Company as reported in the PLATTS Gas Daily publication, in the Daily price survey section under the heading “Transco, zone 5 del.” Midpoint. The Company’s ability to accommodate daily imbalances between Shipper-owned supply and demand is provided on an interruptible basis. On those days when the Company has invoked a BSR pursuant to the provisions of Part 3, Rate Schedule BBS, this ability shall be completely or partially interrupted. In such event, the Shipper will be notified of the applicable interruption in the same manner as, and simultaneous with, notices to Shippers subscribing to Rate Schedule BBS, which notice shall correspondingly serve as the basis of the Cash-Out Shipper’s Authorized Daily Quantity or Authorized Daily Supply. On those days when the Company has invoked such an interruption and on those days when the Company has requested a Shipper taking service under Rate Schedule BBS to interrupt, the Shipper will be subject to the additional charges identified in Section 9.4 of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions for failure to comply with such Authorized Daily Quantity or Authorized Daily Supply.

PART 2 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
Purpose and Effect This Part of the Statement of Operating Conditions contains the general terms and conditions under which Columbia Gas of Virginia, Inc. (“the Company”) will provide NGPA Section 311 Gas Transportation Service in interstate commerce to qualifying shippers, including both end-users and suppliers of natural gas or renewable natural gas, under Rate TS1 (Transportation Service 1) and Rate Schedule TS2 (Transportation Service 2), pursuant to the Blanket Certificate of Limited Jurisdiction issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1. DEFINITIONS
1.1 “Annual Transportation Quantity” means the estimated transportation volume for a Shipper for a 12-month period, as determined by the Company.
1.2 “Authorized Daily Quantity” means that quantity of gas which Shipper is authorized to transport on a specified day when the Company has completely or partially restricted its interruptible services under the provisions of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
1.3 “Authorized Daily Supply” means that quantity of gas which Shipper is authorized to deliver to the Company on a specified day when the Company has imposed an interruption pursuant to Section 9 of this Part or issued a Balancing Service Restriction (“BSR”) pursuant to Part 3 of this Statement of Operating Conditions, restricting a Shipper’s deliveries of gas.
1.4 “Authorized Monthly Quantity” means that quantity of gas which Shipper is authorized to transport during a specified month when the Company has invoked an interruption under the provisions of this Statement of Operating Conditions
1.5 “Authorized Partial Day Quantity” means that portion of a Shipper’s Maximum Daily Quantity of gas that a Shipper is authorized to transport during a specific period of time within a day when the Company has completely or partially restricted its interruptible services under the provisions of this Statement of Operating Conditions. The Authorized Partial Day Quantity shall represent the total amount of gas Shipper is authorized to transport within the time period specified by the Company.
1.6 “Billing Month” means the the period elapsed between consecutive final monthly meter readings, and when referred to in terms of a calendar month, shall mean that billing month the major portion of which occurs in said calendar month.
1.7 “Btu” means one (1) British Thermal Unit.
1.8 “Commission” or “FERC” means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
1.9 “Company” means Columbia Gas of Virginina, Inc.
1.10 “Day” means a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours, ending at 10:00 a.m., Eastern Standard Time.
1.11 “Dekatherm” or “Dth” means a unit of heat equivalent to 1,000,000 Btu’s. The Company uses Dths as the unit of measure for billing Shippers.
1.12 “Dekatherm Multiplier” means a numeric multiplier that is applied to the volume of gas transported, measured in cubic feet, hundred cubic feet (“Ccf”), or thousand cubic feet (“Mcf”) to determine the amount of energy consumed as measured in Dths.
1.13 “Delivery Point” or “Point of Delivery” means the point at which the Company will deliver gas to or for the Shipper. In the case of an End-User, unless otherwise agreed upon, the Delivery Point shall be at the outlet of the Company-owned meter or, when pressure is reduced by the Company after metering, at the outlet side of the Company’s pressure regulator. In the case of a Supplier, the Delivery Point shall be the designated point at which the Company delivers gas on behalf of the Shipper.
1.14 “End-User” means an industrial or commercial entity using gas in its own business or operations.
1.15 "High Pressure" means service being furnished to a Shipper at other than standard distribution pressures.
1.16 "Low Pressure" means service being furnished to a Shipper at standard distribution pressures.
1.17 “Main” means means a distribution line that (i) serves as a common source of supply for more than one service line, or (ii) receives natural gas or renewable natural gas from a Shipper for subsequent transportation by the Company.
1.18 "Maximum Daily Quantity" shall mean the greatest quantity of gas which the Company shall be obligated to deliver to or for the Shipper and which the Shipper shall be entitled to transport during any one day as specified in the Service Agreement.
1.19 "Mcf" shall mean one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas.
1.20 "Month" shall mean the period beginning at 10:00 a.m. EST. on the first "Day" of the calendar month and ending at the same hour on the first "Day" of the next succeeding calendar month.
1.21 “NGPA” means the Natural Gas Policy Act, as amended, 15 U.S.C. §§ 3301-3432.
1.22 "Receipt Point” or “Point of Receipt” means the point or points at which the Company has agreed to receive gas delivered to it by the Shipper, or others on behalf of the Shipper, for transportation and delivery by the Company to or for the Shipper, as set forth in the Service Agreement.
1.23 “Renewable Natural Gas” or “RNG” means gas, consisting primarily of methane, which (1) is derived from biogas produced by landfills, animal farms, wastewater treatment plans, or other sources, and (2) is subsequently processed by removing carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and other constituents in order to convert the biogas into pipeline-compatible gaseous fuel.
1.24 “Service Line” means (i) a distribution line that transports gas from a common source of supply to a Shipper meter or the connection to a Shipper’s piping if there is no Shipper meter or (ii) a pipeline that transports natural gas or renewable natural gas produced or furnished by a Shipper to a Main for subsequent transportation by the Company to a designated Delivery Point. 1.25 “Shipper” means an End-User or Supplier taking gas transportation service under this Statement of Operating Conditions. 1.26 “Shipper’s Premises” means means a contiguous tract of real property owned or controlled by a Shipper, no part or parcel of which, at the time of the original service, is separated from the other by publicly dedicated highways, streets, or roads. 1.27 “Supplier” means an entity producing or furnishing natural gas or renewable natural gas for the use by others. 1.28 “Upstream Pipeline Scheduling Point” or “PSP” means (i) the single point or set of points grouped or designated by an upstream pipeline for purposes of scheduling gas supplies for delivery by such upstream pipeline; or (ii) the single point or set of points grouped or designated by the Company for operational purposes. 1.29 “Virginia SCC” means the Virginia State Corporation Commission.
2. MEASUREMENT 2.1 High Pressure Accounts (a) Measurement Base
The volumetric measurement base shall be one (1) cubic foot of gas at a pressure base of fourteen and seventy-three one hundredths (14.73) pounds per square inch, a temperature base of sixty degrees (60°) Fahrenheit, and without adjustment for water vapor content. (b) Atmospheric Pressure The average absolute atmospheric (barometric) pressure shall be assumed to be fourteen and four-tenths (14.4) pounds to the square inch absolute, irrespective of actual elevation or location of the delivery point above sea level or variations in actual barometric pressure from time to time.
(c) Flowing Temperature
The Company shall determine the temperature of the natural gas flowing through the meter or meters by recorder, from established tables, or by use of temperature sensing elements used in conjunction with electronic measuring devices.
(d) Specific Gravity
The specific gravity of the natural gas shall be determined by the Company, or at Shipper’s option by joint test, at the commencement of transportation hereunder and as often thereafter as reasonably deemed necessary by either Company or Shipper.
(e) Super Compressibility
The deviation of the gas from the laws for ideal gases shall be determined by the Company, or jointly at Shipper’s option, in one of the following ways:
i. The deviation factors shall be computed by approved methods or read from standard tables, in accordance with Report No. 3 of the Gas Measurement Committee of the American Gas Association, as amended, expanded, or tables superseded from time to time. Such computations or selection of factors from tables will be based on the composition of the gas and conditions at point of measurement, and the factors used will be checked by tests of the gas made with such reasonable frequency as found necessary; or
ii. The deviation factors shall be determined by tests of the gas made with such reasonable frequency as found necessary.
(f) Measuring Equipment
Unless otherwise agreed, the Company will own, install, maintain and operate measuring stations equipped with displacement or flow meters and other necessary measuring equipment to determine the volumes of gas transported to the Shipper’s facility, in the case of an End-User, and to the designated Delivery Point, in the case of a Supplier. The gas transported shall be measured in accordance with the latest approved methods in use in the industry generally. Displacement or turbine meter readings shall be adjusted for pressure and temperature conditions. Shipper may install check-measuring equipment, provided such equipment is installed so as not to interfere with the operations of the Company. The Company and Shipper, in the presence of each other, shall have access to the other's measuring equipment at all reasonable times, but, unless otherwise agreed, the reading, calibrating, and adjustment thereof and the changing of charts shall be done only by the owner thereof. Both the Company and Shipper shall have the right to be present at the time of any installing, reading, cleaning, changing, repairing, inspecting, testing, calibrating, or adjusting done in connection with the other's measuring equipment. The records from such measuring equipment shall remain the property of their owner, but, upon request, each will submit to the other its records and charts, together with calculations therefrom, for inspection, subject to return within thirty (30) days after receipt thereof. Shipper shall exercise reasonable care in the installation, maintenance, and operation of its equipment so as to avoid any inaccuracy in the determination of the volume of gas transported. (g) Calibration and Test of Meters
The accuracy of all measuring equipment shall be verified by the owner at reasonable intervals and, if requested, in the presence of representatives of the other party. Neither the Company nor Shipper shall be required to verify the accuracy of such equipment more frequently than once in any thirty (30) day period. If either party at any time desires a special test of any measuring equipment, or if either party at any time observes an error in any such measuring equipment, it will promptly notify the other party, and the parties shall then cooperate to secure a prompt verification of the accuracy of such equipment.
(h) Correction of Metering Errors
If, upon any test, any measuring equipment is found to be in error, such errors shall be taken into account in a practical manner in computing the transportation volumes. If the resultant aggregate error is not more than two percent (2%) fast, then previous transportation volumes corrected in such a manner shall be considered accurate. If, however, the resultant aggregate error exceeds two percent (2%), previous recordings of such equipment shall be corrected to zero error for any period that is known definitely or agreed upon, not to exceed a rebilling period of twelve (12) months. If the period is not known definitely or agreed upon, then such correction shall be for a period extending over one half of the time elapsed since the last meter test, not to exceed a rebilling period of twelve (12) months. All equipment shall, in any case, be adjusted at the time of test to record correctly.
(i) Failure of Measuring Equipment
In the event any measuring equipment is out of service, is found registering inaccurately or other measuring malfunction occurs and the error is not determinable by test, previous recordings, or transportation volumes through such equipment, the amount of natural gas transported for the Shipper shall be estimated using the following methods:
i. By using the registration of any check meter or meters if installed and accurately registering, or, in the absence of (a);
ii. By correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, special test, or mathematical calculation, or, in the absence of both (a) and (b) then;
iii. By estimating the quantity of transportation volumes based on volumes transported during periods under similar conditions and any other relevant metering data, or,
iv. By another method mutually agreed upon by the Shipper and the Company.
The estimated readings so determined shall be used in determining the volume of gas transported for any known or agreed-upon applicable period, not to exceed a rebilling period of twelve (12) months. In case the period is not known or agreed upon, such estimated deliveries shall be used in determining the volume of gas transported hereunder during the latter half of the period beginning on the date of the immediately preceding test and ending on the date the measuring equipment has been adjusted to record accurately, not to exceed a rebilling period of twelve (12) months. The recordings of the measuring equipment during the first half of said period shall be considered accurate in computing deliveries.
(j) Preservation of Records
Both the Company and Shipper shall preserve for a period of at least three (3) years, or such other longer period as may be required by state or federal regulatory agencies, all test data, charts, and other similar records.
(k) Delivery Pressure
The delivery pressure of gas transported hereunder shall be the varying pressures prevailing from time to time in the lines from which the deliveries are made unless Shipper and Company mutually agree to some other delivery pressure which shall be specified in the Service Agreement.
(l) Dekatherm Adjustment
The Company shall apply a Dekatherm Multiplier to metered cubic foot usage to adjust for heating value. In the case of an End-User, this Dekatherm Multiplier shall be calculated monthly based on the most recent reported heating value for the Pipeline Scheduling Point within the Company’s service territory in which the Shipper’s Delivery Point is located. In the case of a Supplier, this Dekatherm multiplier shall be calculated monthly based on the most recent heating value measured at the Receipt Point.
(m) The Quantity of Gas Determined by Meter Reading Except as otherwise indicated in an applicable Rate Schedule, the quantity of gas transported for each Shipper shall be ascertained by a Shipper or Company reading of the meter furnished by the Company or by calculation. The Company’s meters will be read once each month. As to any Shipper whose meter is unable to be read in a month, the transportation volumes for the month shall be determined by calculation on the basis of the Shipper’s previous transportation volumes considering factors such as variations in weather, number of days in the period, and the trend in seasonal transportation volumes, in order to provide as nearly accurate a bill as possible without actually reading the meter.
(n) Dekatherm Adjustment The Company shall apply a Dekatherm Multiplier to metered cubic foot usage to adjust for heating value. In the case of an End-User, this Dekatherm Multiplier shall be calculated monthly based on the most recent reported heating value for the Pipeline Scheduling Point within the Company’s service territory in which the Shipper’s Delivery Point is located. In the case of a Supplier, this Dekatherm multiplier shall be calculated monthly based on the most recent heating value measured at the Receipt Point. (o) Meter Testing The Company shall make a free test of any meter upon written request of any Shipper provided such request is not made more frequently than once each twenty-four months or the meter is not scheduled for a periodic test. For subsequent tests made at the Shipper’s request, the Shipper shall advance the Special Meter Test Charge set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates, to offset the cost of the test. If such tests show the meter to be more than 2% fast, the Special Meter Test Charge shall be refunded and adjustments made to the Shipper’s bill for a period not exceeding twelve (12) months immediately preceding the date of the meter change. If the meter is found not to be more than 2% fast, the Special Meter Test Charge shall be retained by the Company and previous meter readings shall be deemed accurate for billing purposes.
2.2 Measuring Equipment
(a) Location and Maintenance of Company's Equipment
The Company shall have the right to install any gas piping or other equipment as it determines may be needed in connection with transporting gas at a convenient point or points on the property or in the building(s) of the Shipper.
The Shipper shall provide suitable space for the installation of any such equipment, which space shall be accessible for reading, testing, and servicing, and protected from damage by the elements, negligence or deliberate acts of persons.
Meters will normally be installed outdoors; however, when circumstances require, meters may be installed indoors, at the Company's discretion. When large meters are necessary, the Company may require the Shipper to furnish, at the Shipper’s own expense, a suitable building to house the metering apparatus.
All equipment furnished and installed by the Company shall be and remain the property of the Company unless purchased from the Company.
(b) Shipper’s Responsibility
The Shipper shall be responsible at all times for the safekeeping of all Company property installed on Shipper’s Premises, and to that end shall give no one, except the Company's authorized employees, access to such property.
The Shipper shall be liable for the cost of repairs for damage done to Company's property due to negligence or misuse of it by the Shipper or persons on the Shipper’s Premises.
The Shipper shall be liable for all damages which may result from piping, appliances, or equipment of the Shipper, whether or not purchased from or installed by the Company, from the use or misuse other than by the Company of the Company's service or gas transported by the Company, or from the connection of the Company's piping with the Shipper’s equipment.
2.3 Piping and Appliances
All piping, fixtures and appliances on the Shipper’s side of the meter (or on the Shipper’s side of the Receipt Point in the case of Suppliers of natural gas or renewable natural gas) shall be installed and maintained under the sole responsibility and at the expense of the Shipper. Company shall have no responsibility or liability for piping, fixtures, appliances, or any other facilities on the Shipper’s side of the meter. In the event of a suspected gas leak in such piping, fixtures, or appliances, the Shipper shall promptly notify the Company and the Company shall investigate said leakage report at no charge to the Shipper.
The piping, fixtures, and appliances for which the Shipper is responsible shall be maintained by the Shipper in conformity with all State, Municipal, or Federal requirements and with the National Fuel Gas Code. The nature and conditions of this equipment shall be such as not to endanger life or property, interfere with the service to the Company’s other customers, or permit the passage of gas without meter registration and it shall not be used for any illegal purpose. If these conditions are violated, the Company may refuse service or discontinue service without notice until such violations are remedied by the Shipper.
2.4 Use of Gas by Shippers
Shippers which are End-Users agree that no gas, other than that suitable for its use and then available to it through the facilities of the Company, shall be used in the operation of the Shipper’s equipment without previous written notice to the Company.
The service connections and metering apparatus supplied by the Company for each Shipper are definitely limited in capacity, and no additions to the equipment or load connected thereto may be made except upon written notice to the Company.
Shippers which are End-Users shall install only such apparatus and appliances as are suitable for operation with the character of gas volumes transported by the Company without undue disturbance of such volumes, and the gas must not be used by the Shipper in such a manner as to cause objectionable pressure fluctuations in the Company's general distribution system. The Company reserves the right, but shall have no duty, to determine the suitability of apparatus or appliances to be connected to its system, and to determine whether the operation of such apparatus or appliances will be detrimental to its general supply of gas. The Company further reserves the right to refuse to supply gas or to discontinue service until such time as the Shipper conforms to Company requirements.
3. QUALITY OF GAS DELIVERED TO COMPANY
3.1 Quality of Gas at Receipt Point(s) with an Interstate Pipeline.
Gas delivered by or on behalf of Shipper to Company at Receipt Point(s) on an interstate pipeline shall conform to the interstate pipeline’s gas quality standards.
3.2 Quality of Gas at Other Point(s) of Receipt.
Gas delivered by or on behalf of Shipper to Company at Receipt Points(s) other than an interstate pipeline shall be commercially free from oil, water, air, salt, dust, gum, gum-forming constituents, harmful or noxious vapors, or other solid or liquid matter which might interfere with its merchantability or cause interference with proper operation of the lines, regulators, meters, and other equipment of Company or its customers
Shipper will indemnify and hold Company harmless from any suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs, losses and expenses, including but not limited to, attorneys' fees and expenses, arising from personal injury, death, or damage to Company's equipment or facilities or arising from personal injuries, death, or damage to the facilities, products, or equipment of Company's other customers or third parties, or arising from additional hours worked by Company or its other customers or third parties, caused as a result of Shipper’s gas failing to meet the quality specifications set forth herein.

As used herein, renewable natural gas or “RNG” means gas, consisting primarily of methane, which (1) is derived from biogas produced by landfills, animal farms, wastewater treatment plans, or other sources, and (2) is subsequently processed by removing carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and other constituents in order to convert the biogas into pipeline-compatible gaseous fuel.

The Btu content per cubic foot shall be determined by an accepted type of calorimeter or other suitable instrument for a cubic foot of gas at a temperature of sixty (60) degrees Fahrenheit when saturated with water vapor and at a pressure of 14.73 psia. The Btu determination designated by Company shall be made by Company at its expense. Any additional Btu determinations requested by Shipper shall be at Shipper’s expense.
Company may, on a not-unduly discriminatory basis, accept volumes of gas, including renewable natural gas, that fail to meet the quality specifications set forth in this section, if Company determines that it can do so without adversely affecting (1) system operations; (2) the operation of the Company’s equipment; (3) the operation of gas-burning equipment of Company’s other customers; or (4) the quality of public utility service provided by Company. In deciding whether to accept such volumes of gas, the Company shall consider, without limitation, (1) which specifications are not being met; (2) the sensitivity of customer equipment and potential impact on such equipment; (3) Shipper’s plan to improve gas quality; (4) the effect on system supply; (5) interchangeability; (6) the anticipated duration of the quality deviation; and (7) the blending ratio between geological natural gas and RNG in the area of Company’s distribution system where RNG is being injected.
Company shall not be obligated to accept gas which it reasonably believes may adversely affect the standard of public utility service offered by Company, or gas which it reasonably believes may adversely affect the operation of its equipment or the gas-burning equipment of its customers. If any gas delivered hereunder fails to meet the quality specifications set forth herein, Company may, at any time, elect to refuse to accept all or any portions of such gas until Shipper brings the gas into conformity with such specifications.

Notwithstanding a Shipper’s initial establishment of creditworthiness, a Shipper must continue to maintain an acceptable level of creditworthiness. Accordingly, a Shipper’s creditworthiness and the corresponding amount of financial assurance required from the Shipper may be periodically reviewed and updated by the Company to take into account changes in the Shipper’s credit risk profile.
In the absence of an acceptable level of creditworthiness, the Company may require the Shipper to establish and maintain financial assurance through a letter of credit or other form of surety acceptable to the Company as a guarantee of payment for charges that may accrue under this Statement of Operating Conditions.
The amount of financial assurance, if any, to be provided by a Shipper shall be that amount which the Company determines is reasonably required to protect it from adverse financial impacts due to the Shipper’s nonperformance, taking into account the level of risk otherwise imposed on the Company. The consideration of the level of risk imposed on the Company may include, but not be limited to, the level and type of services contracted for by the Shipper; the quantity of gas to be transported and/or banked by the Shipper; the Shipper’s over-all creditworthiness; the Shipper’s past payment history with the Company; and any costs for which the Company may be liable should the Shipper fail to pay for services rendered under applicable Rate Schedules.

9. INTERRUPTION OF SERVICE
9.1 In General
The Company may interrupt gas transportation service provided under this Statement of Operating Conditions in the following situations:
(a) When either the supply available to the Company or the Company’s system delivery capacity is not sufficient to simultaneously serve all non-firm customer requirements and maintain continuous, safe service to all firm customers;
(b) When interruption is necessary in order to perform maintenance or tests or make modifications, repairs, or replacements of the Company’s facilities or the facilities of its upstream suppliers;
(c) When the Company is unable to provide service due to events of force majeure, as defined in Section 5 of this Part;
(d) When Shipper has failed to deliver sufficient quantities of gas to the Company at the PSP behind which its Delivery Point is located or directly to the Company at a Receipt Point behind that PSP and the volumes available to the Shipper under Rate Schedule BBS are insufficient to make up the shortfall. In the case of an End-User, the “shortfall” is the difference between the quantity of gas delivered by the Shipper to the Company at the PSP and the Shipper’s consumption at the Delivery Point. In the case of a Supplier, the “shortfall” is the difference between the quantity of gas delivered to the Company at the Receipt Point and the quantity of gas nominated and scheduled for transportation by the Company to the Delivery Point;
(e) When gas transportation on the Company’s system is occurring by displacement and interruption is necessary due to the limited market absorption capability of the local market area in which the gas supplies are being delivered;
(f) When interruption is necessary in order for the Company to comply with operational orders issued by one or more of the Company’s pipeline suppliers;
(g) When it is necessary to limit deliveries into the Company’s system due to the level of storage inventories or limitations on storage injections or withdrawals and the need for the Company to remain within the operational parameters of the Company’s upstream storage providers and avoid the imposition of monetary penalties or loss of gas supplies; and
(h) When gas delivered to the Company’s system fails to meet the gas quality standards set forth in Section 3 of this Part.
9.2 Manner of Interruption
If service is interrupted pursuant to Section 9.1, the Company shall, to the extent practicable, consider all non-firm services singularly and as a group, in a non-discriminatory manner to determine the order and extent of interruption necessary to protect its firm service obligations. The interruption of service shall be ordered as required by the Company to properly recognize the applicable operating conditions for the affected operating area(s), the expected duration of those operating conditions, the availability of gas and required delivery capacity, and the required reduction in gas deliveries and services at the time in conformity with the Company's public utility obligation.
9.3 Notices of Interruption
(a) Notices of interruption will be given as much in advance as is practicable. The Company will use reasonably appropriate means under the circumstances to notify Shippers, including phone, fax, email, and/or public service announcements. However, the provisions hereof for interruption shall in no way limit or restrict the Company from interrupting services as provided in other provisions of this Statement of Operating Conditions or a Service Agreement. In providing a notice of interruption, the Company will provide the affected Shippers the level of interruption applicable at that time, which will serve as the basis of their applicable Authorized Daily Quantity, Authorized Partial Day Quantity, or Authorized Monthly Quantity.

11. ADDITIONAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
11.1 Heat Content (a) Heating Value of Gas
When Company receives Shipper’s gas from an interstate pipeline for redelivery to Shipper’s facilities or other designated delivery point, the heating value assigned to Shipper’s gas by the pipeline delivering such gas to the Company, as reported monthly by such pipeline to the Company, will be used each billing month to establish the heating value of the gas transported by the Company to the Shipper.
(b) Sampling under Certain Circumstances
If locally produced gas or gas from pipelines other than the pipeline directly delivering Shipper’s gas to Company is introduced into Company's pipeline serving Shipper’s facilities so as to raise a question as to the applicability of the heating value determined by the delivering pipeline, either Company or Shipper may request that gas samples be taken to determine the heating value of the gas received by Shipper at its facilities. The following provisions will apply in the event either party elects to have gas samples taken:
i. The party requesting the sample(s) will pay all costs connected with obtaining the sample(s) and having the sample(s) analyzed.
ii. The gas sample(s) shall be obtained at or in the vicinity of Shipper’s facilities during normal operating hours of the facilities.
iii. The gas sample(s) will be analyzed at a Company testing facility or at a testing facility approved by the Company.
iv. If the analysis is done by an outside testing facility, the testing facility will forward the results directly to Company and Shipper, using a format provided by Company for recording the results of the analysis. If Company performs the analysis, the Company testing facility will forward the results directly to Shipper.
v. Multiple samples taken during any billing month will be averaged to obtain a Btu value; that Btu value will be applied only for that particular billing month. No retroactive adjustments based on Btu readings will be made to billings for any prior month.
vi. The average Btu value obtained from sample(s) during any billing month shall be used to determine the quantities transported by the Company to or for the Shipper only if such Btu value is more than 103% or less than 97% of the delivering pipeline’s Btu value, without adjustment for water vapor content value, provided by the delivering pipeline for that month. STEPS TO ADVANCE VIRGINIA’S ENERGY PLAN (SAVE) RIDER
The Company’s SAVE Rider has been implemented as a component of the Company’s SAVE Plan pursuant to the Steps to Advance Virginia’s Energy Plan Act. The SAVE Rider is comprised of a Projected Factor, which includes a return on investment, revenue conversion factor, depreciation and property taxes associated with eligible infrastructure costs, and a True-Up Factor, which includes carrying costs.
The True-Up Factor will be computed by Rate Schedule at the conclusion of each year of the SAVE Plan as the difference between the actual collections of the Projected Factor and actual eligible infrastructure replacement costs, plus or minus any under- or over-recovered True-Up Factor from the previous SAVE Plan year’s True-Up Factor billing period. For purposes of this calculation, Shippers taking service under Rate Schedule TS1 of this Statement of Operating Conditions will be combined with customers taking intrastate service under Rate Schedule TS1, as approved by the Virginia SCC. Shippers taking service under Rate Schedule TS2 under this Statement of Operating Conditions will be combined with customers taking intrastate service under Rate Schedule TS2, as approved by the Virginia SCC. The results of that calculation will be divided by the estimated number of bills for the True-Up Factor billing period to derive the True-Up Factor applicable during the True-Up Factor billing period.
The SAVE Rider will be equal to the Projected Factor plus or minus the True-Up Factor to be effective with the first billing unit for January of each year of the SAVE Plan. For each year of the SAVE Plan, the SAVE Rider will be billed monthly and shown as a line item on customer bills. The SAVE Riders for Rate Schedules TS1 and TS2 are set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates.

7. BALANCING SERVICE RESTRICTIONS (BSR) a. Definition A Balancing Service Restriction (“BSR”) is a demand for specific action by or on behalf of a Shipper. A BSR will direct Shipper(s) to adjust its consumption or its daily scheduled transportation volumes such that the Shipper’s deliveries to the Company’s system will, as closely as practicable, match its daily consumption or deliveries to one or more designated Delivery Points or a specified portion thereof. All Shippers are subject to the Company’s issuance of BSRs. The issuance of a BSR may result in a partial or complete restriction of Banking and Balancing Service as contemplated in this part. A BSR may be issued on a system-wide basis, by PSP, market or operating area (depending on the designation by a pipeline or the Company for purposes of its operations), by such other geographic area as appropriate under the circumstances, or by individual Shipper.
b. Criteria
The Company has the authority to issue a BSR whenever the Company has a reasonable basis for concluding, based on information available to it at the time, that the sum total of the capacity and supply that it has call upon on a firm basis, exclusive of the Company’s dedicated non-storage peaking supplies, will be insufficient to simultaneously satisfy the Company’s firm service obligations and the non-firm banking and balancing requirements of its interruptible Shippers. For purposes of this section, peaking supplies shall mean those firm supplies having a limited number of day’s availability and that are available to the Company only during the winter operating period (November through March) inclusive of propane and liquefied natural gas.
The following operating conditions shall be considered by the Company when evaluating the need to issue BSRs:
i. actual and forecasted temperatures; ii. actual and estimated demand on the Company’s system; iii. non-peaking capacity and supply that the Company has call upon on a firm basis; and iv. actual and estimated storage activity and storage inventory compared to the Company’s seasonal operating parameters for storage and to the operating standards of its upstream service providers. The need for BSRs will typically be determined the day prior to the actual applicable Gas Day. The actual BSR level called for will generally be based on the Company’s estimate of its balancing capabilities for a given day(s). The Company shall terminate a BSR as soon as its operating conditions permit. c. Types of BSRs
i. BSRs Restricting Under-Deliveries – The Company shall have the authority to direct Shippers to adjust their daily consumption or daily scheduled deliveries, completely or in part, such that the Shipper’s actual consumption or deliveries to one or more designated Delivery Points is no greater than the Shipper’s Authorized Daily Quantity. In such event, a Shipper will be entitled to use gas quantities that are: 1) scheduled and delivered on that day; 2) available pursuant to the Company’s Firm Banking and Balancing Service option; 3) additional banked quantities that may be made available to the Shipper by the Company at its discretion on a best-efforts basis; and 4) available pursuant to a transfer under the Company’s Daily Gas Transfer Service. The sum total of the resultant Company-determined supply entitlement for use by a Shipper or transportation on its behalf shall be the Shipper’s Authorized Daily Quantity.
ii. BSRs Restricting Over-Deliveries – The Company shall have the authority to direct Shippers to adjust their daily scheduled deliveries to an amount no greater than the Shipper’s daily consumption or volumes to be delivered to one or more designated Delivery Points. In such event, the Company shall specify the limitation placed upon the deliveries in excess of a Shipper’s actual daily consumption or deliveries to one or more designated Delivery Points. Such limitations will recognize and include Firm Banking and Balancing Service quantities for subscribing Shippers. The sum total of the resultant Company-determined supply to be received by the Company on behalf of a Shipper shall be the Shipper’s Authorized Daily Supply. The Company may provide an alternative Receipt Point to which a Shipper may choose to deliver quantities of natural gas in excess of the above referenced limitation. The destination of such alternative Receipt Points shall not affect a Shipper’s ability to deliver its Authorized Daily Supply pursuant to the Balancing Service Restriction to its original pipeline scheduling point if the Shipper so chooses.
d. Operational Alert (OA)
An Operational Alert (OA) may be issued by the Company when actual or projected variances between customer-delivered supplies and customer demand are likely to adversely impact the Company’s storage operations and/or the Company’s ability to operate within the contract limitations applicable under the Company’s service provider contracts. An OA is a request for voluntary action on the part of a Shipper. An OA may be issued in an effort to avoid a BSR but shall not be required as a condition to the issuance of a BSR.

ii. The timing, level, and duration of a BSR will be based on the Company's analysis described in subparagraph 7.b above.
